{
  "texts": [
    "Given that AI systems operate within specific sociotechnical environments and AI may have adverse effects on humans (such as privacy, ethics, and decision-making authority), the negative impacts have prompted researchers to consider the development and use of AI systems from a broader sociotechnical context.",
    "For example, Xu et al. [44] argued that HCAI should be applied from the broader perspectives of the ecosystem and sociotechnical environments beyond the current practice that primarily focuses on individual human-AI systems [28].",
    "Thomas et al. [32] argue that HCAI practice should be considered from the perspective of organizational design.",
    "B. Sociotechnical Systems (STS) TheorySociotechnical systems (STS) theory has enjoyed around 60 years of development and application [33], [35], [36], [51], [52], [53], [54], [55], [56], [57], [58].",
    "The STS concept originated from the Tavistock Institute of Human Relations during the 1940s and 1950s [33]."
  ]
}